Citizens’ Rights Group warns against travelling to Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) has warned black people travelling to Missouri against state discriminatory policies and racist attacks.
The group’s statement states: “The NAACP travel note issued for the state of Missouri, valid until 28 August 2017, invites all African-American passengers, visitors and missionaries to be especially attentive and extremely cautious when travelling around the state, given the suspicious racial events of the entire race that have recently taken place across the state and here.”
According to the NAACP, the group was urged to issue a travel alert, both by the recent Missouri Act, which makes it more difficult to win cases involving discrimination, and by the fact that the targets of state law enforcement are unequally targeted by minorities.
“People’s civil rights are being violated.
They are pulled to the edge of the road because of their skin color, they are beaten or killed,” said Rod Chapel, president of the NAACP Missouri branch, in a statement to The Kansas City Star.
“We’ve never had such serious complaints before.”
This is the first such warning issued by the organization for the U.S. state.
The group referred to events such as racist insults towards black students at the University of Missouri and the death of 28-year-old black Tory Sanders from Tennessee.
Sanders died at the beginning of this year in suspicious circumstances after he was hit by gasoline when he drove through the state and was arrested by the Missouri police without being charged with a crime.
In addition, the note refers to a recent report by the Missouri Attorney General showing that black drivers are 75% more likely to be stopped than white drivers in the state.
“Note is meant to make people aware of and warn their families, friends and colleagues about what might happen in Missouri,” Chapel said.
“People must be ready, whether it means taking bail money or informing relatives that they are going through the state.”
Based on the latest data from the FBI’s hate crime reporting program, 100 hate crimes were documented in Missouri in 2015, placing the state at 16th in the state’s section in terms of the number of similar violations.
The travel warning is also in response to Missouri’s new law, which makes it more difficult for a company to sue for discrimination in the search for housing or work.
The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) had previously issued travel notes on Texas and Arizona after these states passed immigration laws obliging local authorities to arrest people for immigration violations because, according to ACLU, this would increase racial profiling.
While travel warnings are usually issued by the Ministry of Foreign Affairs for other countries, interest groups have recently begun to use this measure in response to certain U.S. laws and trends.
Hepatitis: What would anyone know about the different forms of this severe disease?
Hepatitis, or inflammation of the liver, can be caused by five different hepatitis viruses - A, B, C, D and E.
All these viruses cause acute inflammation of the liver tissue.
However, chronic hepatitis B and C, which may develop further into cirrhosis of the liver, i.e., cirrhosis of the liver, and liver cancer, are considered to have a malignancy.
Health Board’s epidemiology adviser, Kutsar says that the symptoms of acute hepatitis are the same for all types of inflammation of the liver - fever, fatigue, loss of appetite, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, gray stools, dark urine, muscle and joint pain, and yellowing of the skin and mucous membranes.
The last sign of the disease also comes from the popular name of inflammation of the liver, jaundice.
In children, hepatitis can occur without signs of illness.
Different types of inflammation of the liver can only be identified based on laboratory data.
Acute hepatitis can turn into chronic hepatitis and go on for decades without any signs of disease, which means that a person may not know anything about his dangerous liver-damaging disease.
Kutsar brings out different forms of hepatitis and describes their course in more detail.
Hepatitis A viruses spread from a sick person and infect us by eating contaminated food or drinking water, by sex, from the stools of an infected person to food, surfaces, objects, mouths, and drug use.
The risk group for hepatitis A infection includes family members and carers, people with chronic liver disease, people who have sex with the infection, men who have sex with men, drug addicts, travellers who visit countries with high prevalence of hepatitis A.
Vaccination can be prevented by vaccination, in particular by recommending vaccination for people who travel a lot and are at risk of hepatitis A.
In addition, it is important to meet daily hygiene requirements: wash or disinfect your hands, wash all fruits and vegetables before using them for food.
Hepatitis B viruses are transmitted by contact with the blood of a sick person, by injecting drugs, tattooing, piercing, using blood-contaminated omelettes (dental brushes, shaving agents), by sex with donor blood, a person suspected of having hepatitis and from a mother with hepatitis to a foetus/non-infant.
The risk group for hepatitis B infection includes injecting drug addicts, infected human sex partners, men having sex with men, newborns of the infected mother, sick family members and carers, healthcare workers, rescue workers and police officers exposed to blood and other body fluids, and passengers visiting countries with high hepatitis B disease.
It is possible to vaccinate people to prevent hepatitis B; in particular, it is recommended to vaccinate people at risk, in addition to people with chronic liver disease, HIV infection, sexually transmitted diseases and diabetes.
Other preventive measures for hepatitis B include: refraining from the use, tattooing and piercing of foreign hygiene and manicure equipment, other sharps equipment and syringe needles, and using a condom in case of infectious sex or avoiding sexual risk behaviour.
Vaccination against hepatitis B is part of the national immunisation plan in Estonia and is free of charge for children.
Hepatitis C viruses are transmitted by contact with the blood of a sick person, by injecting drugs, tattooing, piercing, using blood-contaminated omelettes, by sex with donor blood, a person suspected of having hepatitis, and from a mother with hepatitis to the fetus/ newborn.
The risk group for hepatitis C infection includes injecting drug addicts, infected person’s sex partners, men having sex with men, newborns of the infected mother, sick family members and carers, healthcare workers and police officers exposed to blood and other body fluids, HIV-infected persons and travellers visiting countries with high hepatitis C disease.
The prevention measure for hepatitis C is: refraining from the use, tattooing and piercing of foreign hygiene and manicure equipment, other sharps equipment and syringe needles, and the use of condoms in case of unsafe sex.
There is no vaccine against hepatitis C.
Hepatitis D is caused by the hepatitis D virus, which reproduces in the presence of the hepatitis B virus.
This is why hepatitis D infection occurs with hepatitis B or as a superinfection in patients with chronic hepatitis B.
D Hepatitis viruses are transmitted by contact with blood and other body fluids, by injection needles contaminated with them, sexually transmitted and rarely infected from the mother to the foetus.
The risk group for hepatitis D is chronic hepatitis B virus carriers and people who do not have immunity to hepatitis B.
An effective preventive measure is vaccination with the hepatitis B vaccine, which also protects against infection with the hepatitis D virus.
E hepatitis viruses are transmitted by fecal-oral route with drinking water and food, including low heat-treated meat, fish and shellfish, donor blood, shared syringes and infected mother to the foetus.
Passengers may be infected with hepatitis E in countries with high morbidity.
Preventive measures for hepatitis E include compliance with hygiene requirements: wash or disinfect your hands after going to the toilet, before cooking and eating, after caring for the sick.
Wash fruits and vegetables before consumption, avoid eating low-heat-treated meat, fish and seafood, drink only safe drinking water and avoid the consumption of drugs.
