Blocking critics from Facebook Don’t Apply to the State Office if you don’t tolerate the criticism of voters
The father of our country knew a lot about the unfavorable media coverage.
The Americans loved George Washington, but it didn’t take long for the newspapers to bully him for everything, from domestic politics to his political principles.
The criticism, of course, irritated him.
But he did not force his critics to remain silent.
Because in 1783, Washington said that “freedom of speech may be taken away from us, and in the dark and in silence we may be led to slaughter like sheep.”
This brings me to Maryland Governor Larry Hogan, who has to work hard to be more like Washington.
Hogan’s subordinates have blocked and deleted posts by at least 450 people who posted their opinions on his official Facebook page.
And at the beginning of the week, he was sued by the American Civil Liberties Union ACLU.
The Governor’s official called the action null and void, and the web commentaries chatted about the counter-reactions in the style of “Who cares?”
“It’s just Facebook,” many said.
But it does matter.
And it matters a lot when it comes to a man like Hogan.
It is an amazingly popular Republican governor in a predominantly democratic state.
His approval rate ranks second best among the 50 governors of the country.
Hogan's not a thoughtless, reactive sneezehead.
He has led the state with a firm hand and has remained firmly established in his principles.
In addition, he has used Facebook as the main tool for communicating with his voters quite a bit, for example, by presenting his bald head with a laziness after chemotherapy for the first time.
Thus, the Governor’s page, which is a public forum with official markings, is managed by a staff of taxpayers’ dollars, who are paid to block people visiting it, is unnecessary and, ultimately, dangerous.
Hogan’s spokesman Amelia Chase defended the governor’s behavior in an interview with The Washington Post, arguing that blocking comments was nothing more than moderation.
But it’s too easy to paint a picture of online trolls, spammers, or an angry crowd.
The Post spoke to a number of real people Hogan blocked.
And that's what they are, the real people who communicate with their chosen leaders, the teacher, the owner of the company and the pastor, not the internet trolls.
They all said their comments were respectful, thoughtful, and not at all obscene.
The pastor quoted the Bible in his post, emphasizing Hogan’s Catholicism.
Lakshmi Sarma Ramani, a lawyer from Bowie, Maryland, did not incite anger, but rather hate crimes.
“I politely told him that I was disappointed because he has not responded to hate crimes or other recent news,” he wrote in The Post’s news bulletin.
“I also don’t like the idea that when a lot of people comment on the same topic, someone immediately calls it an indifferent collective effort, rather than admitting that it is a large number of citizens’ concerns.”
What the governor’s officials called a “directed spam attack,” others would probably call “public support.”
The Facebook era allows you to easily match messages by simply blocking a critic or deleting a negative comment.
It is much cleaner than it was in the past, when workers had to be sent out to do the same, so that they could gather newspapers with critical editorials and burn them or arrest the protesters and force them to remain silent.
This is what is happening now, just digitally.
Hogan is not the first state official to be criticized for making Facebook and other social media outlets toothless.
President Trump has been sued by Twitter users who have been blocked from Twitter.
One of the first significant judgments on this subject was made last week in Virginia.
U.S. District Judge James C. Cacheris ruled in Alexandria that the chairman of the Loudoun County Board of Supervisors violated the Constitution’s first amendment when he blocked the voter from his Facebook page.
In Kentucky, ACLU also visited Governor Matt Bevin (R) after using Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be that hard.
In Washington, affordable mail costs had a similar effect to the internet.
Between 1776 and 1800, the number of newspapers quadrupled, and anonymous writers bore a strain on his leadership.
And even then Washington had to face anonymous trolls.
People wrote letters to newspapers under pseudonyms such as Juricola, Valerius, Belisarius, and Portius, making Washington's decisions.
According to historical documents collected within the framework of the online George Washington Letter Collection Project, his cabinet buried under petitions that criticised his views on the friendship, trade and shipping agreements with Britain.
But he did not force them to remain silent.
Freedom of expression, dissent and debate are the cornerstones of our country.
And proper management means accepting it.
