Papua is Indonesia’s poorest province, where 28% of people live below the poverty line, and infant mortality and illiteracy statistics are among the worst in Asia.
But it is also a precious land in Indonesia.
Just 100 km from Pania, a mountainous province of about 153,000 inhabitants in New Jersey, is the largest and most profitable gold mine in the world, Grasberg, owned by Freeport McMoran, a Phoenix-based company.
In 2015, Freeport alone mined around $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper.
In addition, Papua can be proud of its commercial wood reserves, which are estimated to be worth $78 billion.
However, these riches are a source of suffering for the popes, as they result in a suffocating presence of a powerful Indonesian army.
A 2005 study by The New York Times showed that Freeport paid local military and military units around US$20 million between 1998 and 2004, including up to US$150,000 for one officer.
The pope’s efforts to ensure greater autonomy threaten this gold geese and they are ruthlessly renegotiated.
According to human rights activists, more than 500,000 popes have been killed since 1969, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned by the Indonesian military.
According to the Asian Commission on Human Rights, the mass killing of the Papua tribes in the highlands in the 1970s was a measure of genocide.
Last year alone, more than 3,900 peaceful protesters were arrested in the Indonesian police area.
The 2016 report of the Archbishopric of Birsbane, “We will lose everything” includes testimonies of atrocities committed in the previous year, such as extrajudicial executions, torture (according to another report, rape and electric shocks are particularly common) and brutal repression of peaceful demonstrations.
“It’s hard to count the number of victims because such incidents happen every week,” said Andreas Harsono, an Indonesian researcher at Human Rights Watch.
The screws are even more tightly closed, as the natural resources of Papua have caused the influx of new settlers from other parts of Indonesia.
83% of the 3.5 million inhabitants of the province are Christians, but demographics are changing as Muslim economic migrants arrive from the busy islands of Java, Kalimantan, Sumatra and Sulawesi in Indonesia.
