According to local pastor Yavedt Tebai, one of the soldiers was offended by their tone of voice and later returned with four soldiers.
Victims and eyewitnesses say drunk soldiers chased children and beat them with their guns.
Then one of the soldiers shot at the children.
One child, Yulianus Yeimot, aged 16, was beaten so cruelly that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, the nearby election committee building was set on fire, and the next day things escalated even further.
About 1,000 young Papua men, women and children gathered to demand justice on the football field in front of the local police station and military command center.
They wore ceremonial hunting legs and performed the waita dance of the Papua honey pago tribe, during which they ran around and mimicked the birdsong.
Some protestors started throwing stones at the police and the military.
When the evil spirit was aggravated, the soldiers were sent an order via the internal radio. "If the crowd resists more than three times, let them down," it was said, according to an official document seen by TIME magazine, but not published to local media outlets.
Yerimias Kayame (56), the elder of the district of Kego Koto in Enarotal, felt a threat and called for peace to be maintained, asking the crowd to go home.
No one wanted to listen.
“When I turned around, I was suddenly shot in the left wrist,” he told TIME magazine in his bright colors on the veranda of a wooden house.
Kayame still doesn't know who the shooter was, but says the bullet came from the ranks of the assembled soldiers.
“There was a lot of people, there was a lot of shooting,” he adds.
Alfius Youw, a local man, was shot three times by a cousin who saw him shoot.
“I ran to him and examined his body to make sure it was him,” Yohanes told TIME magazine, who, like many Indonesians, uses only one name.
"I saw that he was dead... I kissed him."
Papua Police Chief Inspector Yotje Mende told reporters that his subordinates would only return to the security of their station because it was attacked.
“We must defend ourselves if we are threatened to be killed,” said Pudjo Sulistiya, a police spokesman in Papua.
“It’s a matter of life and death.”
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many injured.
The news of the killings did not reach Jakarta until the next day.
Three weeks later, Jokowi gave a passionate speech in Jayapura, expressing his condolences to the families of the victims and promising to deal with abuses in Papua.
“I want to resolve this case immediately so that it will never happen again in the future,” he said.
In October 2016, Minister of Security Wiranto said that he would establish an extra-judicial mechanism to solve the crimes against human rights committed.
But almost immediately there were excuses as well.
“Most of the crimes happened a long time ago.
Some of them took place in the 1990s and early 2000s.
The point is that we are committed to solving these crimes, but we must follow certain processes,” he said.
Speaking to TIME magazine in Jakarta on June 5, Wiranto withdrew his words, saying he had no intention of creating a mechanism to deal with complaints in Papua.
Instead, he said, “Everything will be resolved by law.”
Wiranto, who has been accused by the UN of crimes against human rights in connection with the deaths of more than 1,000 people in East Timor during the 1999 bloody independence referendum, said that 11 crimes against human rights have already been resolved in Papua, including those in Pania.
The families of the Panic victims accepted such claims with gloomy distrust.
"I have been questioned four times in the last three years, but no progress has been made," Yohanes said.
"I'm tired."
He said that years later, he still lives in fear.
"I'm afraid," he says.
"I'm afraid the military will arrest me, I'm afraid I'm going to be shot."
His brother Yacobus confirmed the opinion that the people of Pania are afraid to break down this incident.
He said he was beaten by the military after he had helped bury four victims.
