In Sweden, a test was carried out among asylum seekers, during which their age was assessed medically with a novel approach. The latest results of the test show that more than 80 percent of the test subjects were assessed older than 18, but not all believe in the accuracy of the results.
The Swedish National Institute of Judiciary (Rätsmedicinalverket) started testing towards the beginning of this year.
The tests were created for a more accurate assessment of age in the asylum application process after the Swedish Migrationsverket was criticised for failing to correctly determine the age of a number of allegedly minor refugees.
To date, migrationverket has sent 6,880 cases for testing and the Institute of Forensic Medicine has issued a total of 2481 test results between mid-March 2017 and 31 July 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) was rated 18 years old or older, and in another 25 cases, the Institute of Forensic Medicine estimated that the test could be “aged 18 or older.”
In 432 cases, it was concluded that a person is "probably younger than 18".
Tests are only used if the age of the person is under question.
