Here are some financial aspects of Neymar’s transition to the French club.
PSG will undoubtedly be able to withdraw such money to recruit Neymar and add it to its starry lineup, given that the team is funded by Qatar’s energy crime ruling family.
Clubs are allowed to spend a lot of money to recruit players, but they need to balance it with legal sources of income that allow them to get out of the football business.
FFP was founded by Michel Platini after he was elected president of UEFA in 2007.
This former French player believed that clubs that fall into large debts in search of success actually deal with fraud and risk decomposition if banks or owners were to give up support.
Since 2011, FFP has focused on monitoring the losses rather than the debts of clubs.
This change means that the business model that Roman Abramovich first used in 2003 in Chelsea - to buy a club with potential and then to make a huge expense to improve the team and create a global brand - is more difficult to implement.
During the current three-year assessment period of FFP, which runs until 2018, clubs can bear losses of up to EUR 30 million.
And despite Platini’s disgraceful rejection of the presidency in 2015, his successor, Aleksander Ceferin, is still committed to preventing excessive spending.
"The FFP is certainly not dead, and we will undoubtedly continue to strengthen these rules in the future," Andrea Traverso, a supervisor at the UEFA FFP, told The Associated Press last week.
