Bank of England keeps interest rates at 0.25%
The Bank of England is expected to report that interest rates will remain at the same level as the weak economic growth and the easing of inflation have softened speculation about the rise.
The Bank of England has warned that economic growth will remain sluggish, as the household’s tight incomes have put interest rates on hold.
The policy makers of the Bank’s Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) voted in favour of keeping the 6:2 ratios at 0.25%, and fewer members are calling for an increase this month, as slow economic growth has weakened support for the rise.
In its quarterly inflation report, the Bank cut its 2017 growth forecast by 1.7% and its 2018 growth forecast by 1.6% and warned that the pressure on household incomes will remain, as inflation is still expected to rise close to 3% in the autumn.
At the same time, the Bank also signalled that the increase in rates will be necessary in the next few years to curb inflation caused by Brexit, and the financial markets may need a higher than expected increase in loan costs.
Members also voted in favour of the partial withdrawal of the mammoth package, which was launched a year ago as a result of Brexit.
The bank will close a fixed-term funding scheme in February, offering cheap financing to banks, although it said that it is now expected to offer <0xC2><0xA3>15 billion more under this scheme, i.e. <0xC2><0xA3>115 billion.
In the minutes of the decision on the rate, the Bank says: "The average forecast of the MPC will remain ineffective in the near future, as the difficult situation of real household incomes will continue to have an impact on consumption."
With regard to rates, it was reiterated that in order to mitigate inflation, it is necessary to 'push up some of the financial policies' and 'somewhat more' than the markets are expected to do.
The stock exchange is currently forecasting its first increase in the third quarter of next year and its second increase in 2020.
However, the bank stressed that all kinds of jumps are gradual and limited.
The Bank’s reduced growth forecasts for this and next year are comparable to those for May of 1.9% and 1.7%.
The forecast for growth of 1.8 per cent in 2018 remained unchanged.
After this news, the pound’s exchange rate for the dollar and the euro fell.
The nail dropped 0.5% to USD 1.31 and 0.4% to EUR 1.11.
The decision not to make changes is due to recent disappointing growth figures, which have dampened the growing expectations of GDP growth in the second quarter from 0.2% in the previous three months to 0.3%.
The bank says that growth is likely to remain at 0.3% in the third quarter, although at the end of the year it will start to pick up slightly.
The Bank’s latest inflation report gave little reason to welcome households suffering from rising inflation and a relentless rise in wages, saying that the situation would get a little worse before it got better.
It was added that monetary policy could not prevent a hit on income in the next few years, but a significant wage recovery is expected towards the end of the three-year forecast.
Due to the weak pound, the economy is also stimulated by growing demand for British production, which partly compensates for lower consumer spending.
The decision comes a year after the rates were taken in August, 0.25% after the shocking EU referendum, which caused a sudden weakening of the pound.
According to the Bank, it is likely that it will take four years to fully blow up prices and the economy.
Before the Bank’s last decision, there was a growing demand for a rate increase, as inflation had increased pressure on households in distress; in July, three policymakers called for a rate increase of 0.5%.
Inflation fell by 2.6% last month, compared to 2.9% in June, although the bank said it was expected to do so, and in the coming months it is expected to rise again.
The bank said that the excess increase compared to the 2-percent target was due to a completely weak pound.
