The stock exchange seems particularly favourable to those whose current transactions are about to come to an end, as refinancing, often without a fee and at a low rate, has become increasingly popular.”
The NHS is writing a controversial HIV drug for 10,000 people.
Since September, patients have access to “transformative” HIV prevention treatment after a battle in the Supreme Court over whether NHS should fund the drug.
NHS England reported that it is now estimated that during the initial three-year clinical trial, public health will make available to 10,000 people pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) tablets, which are administered prior to intercourse and have shown a reduction of approximately 86% in the risk of infection in high-risk people.
The NHS agreed to finance the clinical trial after the appeal court supported the Supreme Court’s decision last year that the NHS would be able to pay for PrEP, despite the agency’s own claims that the medicine should be financed by local authorities instead.
Simon Stevens, Executive Director of NHS England, welcomed this move, which was announced Thursday, as a “new major intervention,” while the National AIDS Fund (NAT) described it as “a pivotal moment.”
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield are among the first to start registering people. In October, more clinics will be added before the program is implemented everywhere in England by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a course of HIV medicines taken before intercourse to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
The results of clinical trials show that PrEP significantly reduces the transmission of HIV among people at risk of infection.
Taking PrEP before intercourse means that there are enough certain drugs in the human body that prevent HIV infection.
Such drugs can be taken daily or at the latest two hours before intercourse.
Candidates suitable for treatment include gay or bisexual men, transgender people and people whose partners are infected with HIV and who do not receive treatment.
Clinics identify suitable people who are willing to participate in a clinical trial, including men, women, transgender people and those whose HIV partner is not receiving antiretroviral therapy.
People who live in England and have chosen a family doctor will also be able to register their wish to participate in the local sexual health clinic participating in the program.
The program costs <0xC2><0xA3>10 million and NHS England signed a contract to receive medicines this week after an international procurement procedure.
The aim of the clinical trial is to assess the real potential of PrEP by gathering clinical evidence of who the product is intended for and how it is consumed and applied in a large picture.
Stevens said: “This new comprehensive intervention should complement and amplify the widespread and increasingly successful fight against HIV transmission.
This is yet another milestone in more than three decades of struggle with one of mankind’s greatest health problems.”
Deborah Gold, executive director of NAT, said: “This is a pivotal moment in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, if properly targeted at those who need it and are part of a risk group, offers an opportunity to change the HIV epidemic in England.
Since September, people at high risk for HIV in England, through this NHS-funded clinical trial, have access to a powerful new tool that is individually manageable and does not depend on negotiations with a partner, thereby improving many lives.
We warmly welcome this announcement."
Ian Green, Managing Director of Terrence Higgins, said: "It is now vital to ensure that the clinical trial across the country is pushed to speed and that no HIV risk group member is left behind.
Now that PrEP clinical trial drug has been acquired, we are on our way to protecting more than 10,000 people who are at risk of contracting HIV.
Sharon Hodgson, the shadow Minister of Public Health, said: “The start of the clinical trial of PrEP is very welcome and very late after months of delay and dragging the feet of the government.
Evidence shows how big changes this drug can bring to the prevention of HIV and its cessation of the spread of life-changing infection.
This clinical trial takes us one step closer to understanding the full benefits of PrEP.
It is now important that the clinical trial be deployed across the country as soon as possible to protect people who are exposed to HIV and to bring us one step closer to stopping the spread of HIV in society."
