Trump’s new chief of staff plans to limit the President’s media consumption.
Others have tried and failed.
Maybe John F. Kelly can do it.
In that case, he would be the first.
Politico writes that the White House’s new chief of staff plans to limit the flow of information, including news, that will reach President Trump, in the hope that it will keep the chief in smoother water.
Here's an excerpt from reporter Josh Dawsey:
When White House’s new Chief of Staff John F. Kelly met with senior officials on his first working day, he pointed out a key problem at President Donald Trump’s White House, which he planned to solve by getting bad information into the hands of the president.
Kelly told officials that the information had to go through him, whether on paper or at meetings, because the president would make better decisions if he was given good information.”
Kelly’s diagnosis seems completely logical, but others have tried it, and they have failed to tame Trump by monitoring his media consumption.
President Trump’s relationship with television goes back decades, and even now that he’s in the White House, his TV viewing habits haven’t gone anywhere.
“When the candidate Trump was upset about the unfair media coverage, he was paid to show that he was also honestly reflected in the affected publications,” former campaign adviser Sam Nunberg told Politico in February.
According to Politico Tara Palmer, “six former campaigners say the key to managing Trump’s Twitter habits is to ensure that his personal media consumption also contains a strong sense of praise.”
All right.
But the idea that Trump’s use of Twitter has ever been “controlled” is ridiculous.
Perhaps these campaigners know something the rest of us don’t know that Trump’s tweets would have been even more flammable without their interventions.
We’ll probably never know about tweets that Trump didn’t post.
When his assistants were able to save him a couple of times from trouble, their efforts were worth it.
But no one has been able to stop Trump from constantly creating controversy.
Part of the problem is that in the White House, which consists of competing clicks, people are exclusively trying to advance their own interests by providing Trump with material that supports their worldviews, but may not always be trustworthy.
In May, Politico wrote about the tendency of counselors to feed the president with information of strategic questionable value.
One of the examples described by reporter Shane Goldmacher is as follows:
“Current and former Trump subordinates say that Trump may respond to a negative press, especially harmful news leaks, explosively, with an obsession with identifying their source.
This was also the case at the end of February, when someone gave the President a horribly printed copy of an article on the website GotNews.com, which belonged to Charles C. Johnson, which accused the deputy chief of staff Katie Walsh of being the White House’s “source of multiple communications.”
It doesn’t matter if Johnson has been permanently blocked from Twitter because of a mockery, or if he didn’t provide any concrete evidence, or if he’s been making false accusations in the past and taking them back.
Trump read the article and began to inherit Walsh from his subordinates.”
Goldmacher added that the then Chief of Staff, Reince Priebus, and Rob Porter, head of the White House Office, “have tried to establish a system for managing and documenting documents reaching Trump.”
How did it work?
Kelly's trying to do exactly the same thing three months later.
He may prove to be a more effective leader of Priebus, but Trump is still impulsive and his assistants are still competing for influence.
These unchanging factors make Kelly's mission very difficult.
