Eesti Pank purchased bonds for EUR 149 million under the public sector asset purchase programme of the euro area central banks in July, while the central bank’s bond portfolio grew to EUR 4.36 billion.
The central bank does not publish more detailed information about the purchases.
In response to the interpellation of the members of the Riigikogu, the President of the Estonian Bank Hardo Hansson has explained that the Eurosystem central banks’ asset purchase programme includes three different purchase programmes: covered bonds in the financial sector, ABSs and public sector bonds (PSPPs).
The central bank buys bonds from the market to encourage investors who sell bonds to invest money elsewhere.
As a result of purchases, the return on lower-risk assets decreases and this motivates investors to take higher risks.
As a general rule, under the public bond purchase programme, each central bank buys its own government bonds, while other national bonds are not purchased.
Since the Estonian state has not issued bonds, the Bank of Estonia will make so-called replacement purchases within the limits of the volume allocated to them.
Replacement purchases are also made by central banks in countries where the offer of bonds corresponding to the purchase plan is limited.
According to Hansson, Eesti Pank generally buys bonds from European institutions, such as the European Financial Stability Fund and the European Investment Bank.
Eesti Pank will purchase bonds as part of the asset purchase programme as of March 2015.
In the meantime, Elering bonds were also acquired, but from June 2016 Eesti Pank will no longer buy Elering bonds.
As of June, both Elering and Eesti Energia will be bought by the Finnish central bank on behalf of the euro area central banks.
