The rules for handling genetically modified crops must be clear
The Ministry of Rural Affairs sent the Bill on Amendments to the Release of Genetically Modified Organisms into the Environment Act (GMOVS) and the Plant Protection Act to the Coordination Circle.
The amendment to the Act waives the creation of a separate database for both the locations of genetically modified (GM) crops and the handlers, for which the plant health register will be used in the future.
In addition, the GM crop manager’s obligation to have a prior agreement with a beekeeper within the prescribed range is amended.
Although genetically modified crops are not currently grown in Estonia, we consider it necessary to have clear rules for the coexistence of genetically modified and unmodified crops.
At least until the decision to declare Estonia GMO-free has been made," said Sigmar Suu, head of the Plant Health Department at the Ministry of Rural Affairs.
"At the same time, it must be taken into account that the measures developed must be objective and proportionate, take into account the costs and administrative burden for both the private and public sectors," he added.
The Bill repeals the provisions related to the location of GM crops in the GMOVS and the dataset of handlers and the training of handling, and establishes the requirements for the handling of GM crops and the commencement of economic activities.
In particular, as regards beekeeping, the GM crop grower’s current obligation to inform beekeepers of the commencement of GM crop cultivation is replaced by an obligation to reach an appropriate agreement with beekeeper prior to the commencement of cultivation.
The Bill has been sent to the ministries for approval.
All interested parties have the opportunity to consult the information system of the drafts and to submit their opinion to the Ministry of Rural Affairs if they wish.
The planned changes will affect, in particular, persons active in the field of crop production, beekeepers and the Agricultural Board.
In the European Union, including Estonia, it is allowed to grow only one GM crop - maize MON 810.
Until now, however, no Estonian farmer has been interested in growing GM crops.
This is due to the fact that there is no maize pest in Estonia, a European seaweed for which maize MON 810 is resistant.
The varieties of this maize line have also been bred in southern regions and this maize is not suitable for our climate.
The Ministry of Rural Affairs has commissioned studies in 2015 and 2016 to detect possible contamination with GM organisms in seeds of various varieties of summer rape, maize and soya grown in Estonia.
The results of the analysis of the samples taken showed that the seeds did not contain foreign genes and the results of the study concluded that the seeds of rape, maize and soya varieties grown in Estonia did not contain genetically modified organisms.
In turn, it can be concluded that there is no deliberate cultivation of genetically modified crops in Estonia and that there has also been no accidental contamination.
